The epidemic curve (Figure 2) shows the maintenance of viral circulation in the period of low occurrence (June to September), when low temperatures and rainfall generally imply conditions less favorable to transmission. Epizootics in NHP confirmed in the states of Sao Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, Espirito Santo and Minas Gerais, detected in the same affected areas and close to the previous outbreak (2016/2017), indicated the maintenance of regional transmission and risk to human populations. In the monitoring period 2016/2017 until EW 18, 1548 epizootics were confirmed in NHP, of which 353 met laboratory criteria, while in the current period (2017/2018), 738 epizootics were confirmed (by laboratory) (Figure 3).

Figure 2 [graph]. Distribution of epizootics in NHP notified to SVM/MS, by EW of occurrence and classification during the monitoring period 2017-2018 (July 2017-June 2018), Brazil up to week 18.

Figure 3 [graph]. Distribution of epizootics in NHP notified to SVM/MS, by EW of occurrence and classification during the monitoring period 2016-2017 (July 2017-June 2018), Brazil up to week 18.

Surveillance of human cases
---------------------------
Surveillance of human cases is done through the notification of cases with symptomatology compatible with YF. Every suspected case must be promptly communicated by telephone, fax or email to the authorities, (within 24 hours), as it is a serious disease with risk of dispersion to other areas of national and international territory. It is important to fill out the Investigation form of the Notification of Injury Information System (Sinan).

In the monitoring period 2017/2018 (July / 2017 to June / 2018), up to EW18, 6525 suspected cases of YF were reported, of which 3963 were discarded, 1301 remain under investigation and 1261 were confirmed. Of the total confirmed cases, 409 resulted in death (fatality of 32.4 percent [394 / 1257]). Most confirmed cases were reported in the Southeast region (99.9 percent [1260 / 1261]) (Table 2).

